	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64266250"><p><div class="quote"><p>Could be the guy got old and lost his edge.  Happens.</p></div><p>He took the role in 2021. In the previous three years there were <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/mollybohannon/2024/02/21/head-of-boeing-737-max-program-leaving-immediately/" title="forbes.com">four other people</a> [forbes.com] at that same position.  As this comment from <a href="https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/boeing-737-max-program-head-renton-plant-leaves-planemaker-memo-2024-02-21/" title="reuters.com">a Reuters article</a> [reuters.com] relates, removing him won't fix the problem. The problems at Boeing are cultural.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>"Firing the head of the MAX program was likely a matter of time, but I don&rsquo;t think it means very much," said Richard Aboulafia, managing director of aerospace consultancy AeroDynamic Advisory and a Boeing critic. &ldquo;The company&rsquo;s problems are cultural, with the tone being set from the top.&rdquo;</p></div><p>Another quote from the same article had this to say:</p><p><div class="quote"><p>David Nolletti, New York-based head of the aerospace practice at business services consultancy Riveron, said the change would affect how the program is managed and could signal more changes.</p><p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not just a figurehead position,&rdquo; Nolletti said.</p><p>&ldquo;I think we&rsquo;ll see more changes at Boeing as they evaluate their position and how their programs are performing.&rdquo;</p></div><p>In addition, <a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKBN2B42OU/" title="reuters.com">this article</a> [reuters.com] from when Clark was added in:</p><p><div class="quote"><p>Clark is the fifth person in four years to take the helm of the program, which has over the years grappled with quality shortfalls, parts shortages and then the safety ban following the crashes</p></div><p>In other words, there's more going on than just one person.</p></div>
	</div>

